Diagnosis. Surstylus large, with 1 strong prensiseta apically and several thin, long setae ( Figs 2 , 8 , 12 , 16 , 20 , 24 , 28); 10th sternite mostly narrowed, nearly arcuate, with 1 pair of projections posterolaterally ( Figs 3 , 9 , 13 , 17 , 21 , 25 , 29); gonopods (dorsal arch in
Bächli et al . 2004
) with 1 pair of projections sublaterally ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30); aedeagus mostly separated from basally and with cilia ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30).

Male terminalia: Epandrium with setae and pubescence ( Figs 1 , 7 , 11 , 15 , 19 , 23 , 27). Surstylus separated from epandrium, with thin, long setae on margins of outer surface and inner surface ( Figs 2 , 8 , 12 , 16 , 20 , 24 , 28). Cercus separated from epandrium, setigerous, sometimes with sporadic pubescence ( Figs 1 , 7 , 11 , 15 , 19 , 23 , 27). Hypandrium anteromedially protruded, connected with base of aedeagus by articulating plate like paramere ( Sidorenko 1997 , 1998 ) but mostly lacking sensilla ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30). Paramere (paraphysis in
Bächli et al . 2004
) absent ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30). Gonopods forming posteromedian lobe, sclerotized, laterally contiguous to posterior ends of hypandrium ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30). Aedeagal apodeme slender, contiguous to base of aedeagus ( Figs 4 , 10 , 14 , 18 , 22 , 26 , 30).

Female terminalia (
Figs 5, 6
): Epiproct and cerci not pubescent; oviscapt (8th sternite) with numerous, minute spinules; hypoproct with numerous setae and pubescence.
